merican tech entrepreneur and a South Korea legal expert who will be Samsung Electronics' second-ever female director. The third new independent member is a semiconductors expert and Seoul National University professor.</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>The board had previously consisted of nine Korean men, including five independent directors. There are four holdovers on the new board, which will have six independent members.</Para><Para>In the past, Samsung Electronics had foreigners serve as independent directors—though none since 2010. The company's only previous female director left in 2016 after a three-year term.</Para><Para>Foreign investors and corporate governance advocates have said Samsung —one of South Korea's largest family-run conglomerates, or chaebols—prioritizes the needs of the company's ruling Lee family over its minority shareholders. A <ELink type="webpage" ref="http://www.wsj.com/articles/samsung-group-firms-to-vote-on-making-boards-more-independent-1457610101">stronger, independent board</ELink> would help address this concern, those critics say.</Para><Para>"We want a functioning board rather than a shadow board," said Park Yoo-kyung, a Hong Kong-based director at a subsidiary of Stichting Pensioenfonds ABP, Europe's largest pension fund. The Netherlands-based fund owns Samsung Electronics shares.</Para><Para>Board meetings are expected to continue being conducted in Korean.</Para><Para>Shareholders will want to see evidence the new-look board is actually calling the shots at the company—and not Lee Jae-yong, the firm's de facto leader and grandson of its founder.</Para><Para>Despite a run of record profits, Samsung Electronics has faced a leadership vacuum as Mr. Lee recently <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/samsung-heir-lee-jae-yong-convicted-of-bribery-1503642785">spent about a year behind bars</ELink> for his involvement in a government corruption scandal that riveted South Korea. He was <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/samsung-heir-lee-jae-yong-to-be-freed-from-prison-by-appeals-court-1517813046">released in February</ELink>, when an appeals court cut his five-year sentence.</Para><Para>Some investors were expecting Samsung Electronics to name foreign board members without any ties to South Korea. The company has told some large shareholders it would welcome a list of possible foreign candidates for future years, and Ms. Park said there were plans to provide such suggestions.</Para><Para>"From an investors' perspective, this is a modest step, low-hanging fruit," she said of the three new board additions. "One big step. That's what we are expecting."</Para><Para>In 2019, the terms of Samsung's three other independent directors will expire, meaning the potential for at least three new outsiders if those members don't seek re-election. According to company bylaws, Samsung's board could grow to as large as 14 members.</Para><Para>Mr. Lee, officially a Samsung vice chairman and a board member, has kept a low profile since being released from prison and didn't attend Friday's shareholder meeting. His case will be heard by the Supreme Court later this year.</Para><Para>At the meeting, Samsung shareholders also approved a leadership shake-up announced last October, including the appointment of three CEOs to oversee Samsung's mobile, electronics components and consumer electronics divisions.</Para><Para>Lee Sang-hoon, Samsung's former chief financial officer, became the board's chairman—the first non-CEO to hold that role. The three CEOs and Lee Sang-hoon also joined Samsung's board.</Para><Para>In November 2016, Samsung made a series of pledges to improve shareholder value and <ELink type="webpage" ref="http://www.wsj.com/articles/elliotts-new-push-to-revamp-samsung-fits-with-firms-own-plans-1475750421">boost transparency</ELink> after U.S. activist hedge fund Elliott Management Corp. revealed an <ELink type="webpage" ref="http://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-hedge-fund-elliot-faces-probe-into-samsung-stake-1456392471">ownership stake</ELink> in the South Korean firm. An Elliott spokesman declined to comment on the board election.</Para><Para>Over the past year, Samsung has boosted dividends, extended a share-repurchase program and said it would cancel some $35 billion in treasury shares, a type of holding that has long concentrated voting power in the hands of ruling conglomerate families.</Para><Para>Samsung ranks highest among South Korean firms for corporate governance but has a way to go before matching global standards for big companies, said Lee Won-il, who advises large investors on corporate-governance issues.</Para><Para>"Samsung is at least at the C-level for corporate governance based on a U.S. standard, and it's heading toward a B grade," said Mr. Lee, a veteran asset-management executive. "It's going to take time for us to see American-style productivity from the board of directors."</Para><Para>Write to Timothy W. Martin at <ELink type="webpage" ref="mailto:timothy.martin@wsj.com">timothy.martin@wsj.com</ELink></Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field">By Timothy W. Martin </Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field"></Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">Copyright 2018 Dow Jones &amp; Company, Inc. All Rights Reserved. </Copyright></Article></ArchiveDoc><AdocTOC adoctype="article"><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/ArchiveDoc::Article" type="arttext"></Item><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/InvertText" type="invtext"></Item><Item subtype="primary" size="0" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/samsung-electronics-moves-to-expand-and-diversify-boardand-critics-shrug-1521777834" type="webpage"></Item></AdocTOC></DistDoc>

